<p>The 100th anniversary of the First World War comes at a time of unprecedented advances in information technology - everyday, we are extending the ways in which the world interacts, communicates, shares knowledge and experiences. How can we imagine the isolation of Australia in 1914, so far from the front line in Europe? The heart-wrenchingly slow pace at which news, letters from loved ones, and people moved across the globe? Drawn into a war XXX km away, our fledgling nation formed powerful bonds at home, and lasting connections to abroad, that continue to influence what it means to be an Australian today.</p>